    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0297b01b-b4dc-4171-9931-56a5810099b9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 56-year-old man with a sturdy, slightly overweight build who moves carefully and rises from chairs with visible stiffness. He often shifts his weight away from his right knee and walks with a mild antalgic limp that becomes more noticeable after he has been on his feet for several hours. His face shows the tired patience of someone who has been living with chronic joint pain for years, and he sometimes rubs the front and inner side of his knee while talking. On examination days he usually wears practical work clothes and supportive walking shoes, reflecting an active but increasingly limited daily routine.\n\nHe works as a warehouse supervisor, a job that still requires frequent walking, stair climbing, and long periods of standing on concrete floors. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys weekend fishing, light gardening, and watching local football with close friends, but he has gradually cut back on these activities because knee pain flares after exertion. He lives with his spouse, is socially connected to a few longtime friends, and tries to remain independent, though his family has noticed that he avoids kneeling, squatting, and longer outings.\n\nHis symptoms are typical of knee osteoarthritis: deep aching pain in the knee that worsens with activity, morning stiffness lasting under 30 minutes, crepitus, and intermittent swelling after overuse. He describes difficulty going down stairs, discomfort after prolonged sitting, and reduced confidence with twisting movements. The pain is usually manageable at rest but becomes more intrusive by late afternoon, especially after busy workdays.\n\nLifestyle-wise, {patientName} is a former recreational runner who is now largely sedentary outside work because movement has become unpleasant. He occasionally drinks beer on weekends, does not use illicit drugs, and smokes very rarely, mainly in social settings in the past. His diet is mixed and convenient rather than structured, contributing to gradual weight gain over the last decade, which likely adds mechanical stress to his knee joint."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:699a46ac-4127-4e3b-86c9-94f1d1734bd1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports several years of gradually progressive right greater than left knee pain, with worsening over the past 18 months. He recalls a twisting sports injury in his 30s and later underwent arthroscopic meniscectomy, after which he recovered well for many years. He has not had recent hospitalizations, but he has made repeated primary care and orthopedic visits for worsening knee pain and reduced mobility.\n\nComorbidities include obesity and mild essential hypertension. He uses over-the-counter analgesics intermittently and has tried a knee brace, activity modification, and brief physical therapy with partial relief. His work involves prolonged standing and walking, which aggravate symptoms. He denies fever, inflammatory small-joint symptoms, or acute trauma.\n\n{patientName} is allergic to penicillin, which caused urticaria in early adulthood. He is increasingly frustrated by reduced exercise tolerance and has gained weight as his activity level has fallen. Sleep is occasionally disturbed after physically demanding days because knee discomfort intensifies in the evening."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
